messages.text: When are you going to start calling me Dad?
Never. You’re my stepdad, not my dad—
And besides, you’ve only been married to Mom for six months.
But listen, I need your help.
I’m 10 miles from home, near the abandoned house on Route 23—
I’m okay. I hit an animal…
I killed it 🙁 I feel so sad.
Stay in the car till I get there.
I’m outside already – standing next to it.
No, the fox’s blood. It’s splattered all over the windshield.
Yeah, the front hood is smashed…
That’s okay. We can fix the car.
But his hair and blood is all over it—
It has grey fur and yellow eyes.
What does its snout look like it?
There could be at least another one ANYWHERE.
Okay, I’ll get back in the car…
Wait — I see headlights in the distance.
I think someone is stopping to help me.
Yeah, it’s an old pickup truck.
It’s a kid from my high school.
It’s a small town. I know everyone here.
Because he’s a hunter like you.
Does he have a shotgun in his truck?
I told you — wolves hunt in packs.
I want to save the wolf.
Gracie – this is not the time for your liberal garbage.
ASK BILLY IF HE HAS A GUN.
How much is the wolf moving?
Do you think we can save it?
Does Billy have anything else in his truck?
Good. Tell him to bash the wolf’s head in.
Billy smashed the wolf’s head like you said…
It’s still moving its poor little head…
I’m standing in front of your car.
What the hell is going on?
Why did you tell me your car was wrecked?
Is this some sort of prank?
The back of Ralph’s neck starts to prickle.
Ralph turns around and sees Gracie—
And it’s pointed directly at his head.
Gracie…what are you doing with that thing?
I found this in your trophy room.
This gun has killed a LOT of innocent animals, hasn’t it?
Maybe it’s time it killed a human.
Do you even know what you’re saying?
I know exactly what I’m saying.
Shut up! You’re nothing like my father.
My father was kind and good—
He wouldn’t hurt a fly. But you…
Ralph is cut off by the sound of tires crunching over gravel.
Gracie’s Mom jumps out of the driver’s seat.
Oh my god, what are you doing?!
Mom runs up and stands between Gracie and Ralph.
Ralph deserves this. He kills all the time, and yet you love him.
How could you LOVE someone like that?
You used to love Dad. Remember him, Mom?
How could you love this monster now?
With her hands raised, Mom takes a few steps toward her.
Gracie notices the tears falling down her mom’s cheeks.
But she’d never want to hurt her mom.
Mom rushes to Gracie and pulls the gun out of her hands.
Mom envelopes her in a hug.
It’s okay Gracie. Everything’s going to be alright.
It…it was never loaded. I never would have actually shot Ralph.
I know you wouldn’t have, honey.
Ralph takes a step toward Gracie.
Gracie, why didn’t you tell me you were mad?
I didn’t know how you felt about my hunting.
Gracie looks up from her Mom’s embrace and wipes her nose.
You would have just called it my liberal garbage.
I should have tried harder to get to know you.
If you want me to stop hunting, I will.
Gracie runs to Ralph, and he gives her a big bear hug through her sobs.
Gracie, Mom and Ralph walk back to the car, hand in hand.
Once they get home, Ralph throws out all his guns.
And Gracie finally starts calling him Dad.
